fields.name: L'Aquila
fields.overallimpact:
The earthquake caused 308 deaths and nearly 1,200 injuries of which 202 were serious. This was the deadliest earthquake in Italy since the November 23, 1980 earthquake in the region of Campania and the most destructive earthquake in L’Aquila since the series of three earthquakes that devastated the wider region in January 14, 16 and February 2, 1703 killing at least 10,000 people. 

203 people died in L’Aquila (a city of 73,000 inhabitants and many more thousands of non-resident students of the L’Aquila University), while in the village of Onna 38 out of circa 350 inhabitants were killed. 

The hospital at L'Aquila, where many of the victims were brought, suffered damage in the 4.8 aftershock which occurred one hour after the main earthquake and had to be partly evacuated. Damage to L’Aquila’s and wider regions’ historic buildings and churches was also quite severe. 

In total almost 4,000 buildings collapsed or were damaged beyond repair, while another 70,000 buildings were damaged but repairable, with the number of long-term homeless reaching 49,000 people. 

The Italian government in a report to the EU estimated the cost of the earthquake at just over €10 billion while insured losses reached 250 million US$.

fields.eventnarrative:
On Monday April 6th 2009, at 03:32 local time, an earthquake of moment magnitude 6.3 struck the town of L’Aquila and surroundings in Central Italy’s Abruzzo region. 

The April 6, 2009 main shock was preceded by an earthquake swarm which started at the end of 2008; the largest earthquake of this swarm had magnitude 4.1 and occurred on March 30th 2009. 

The shallow focal depth (9 km) and proximity of the epicentre (42.33°N, 13.33°E) to the city of L’Aquila and surrounding villages meant that damage was quite severe and loss of life occurred mostly due to collapse of old masonry and some reinforced concrete buildings (e.g. a student dormitory of L’Aquila University etc.). 

The USGS’s PAGER system estimated that during this earthquake 88,000 people were exposed to intensity VII or greater.

fields.overallimpact:
In the USGS EXPO-CAT database it is estimated that during this earthquake 4,434,000 people were exposed to intensity VII or greater, of which 46% were in rural areas.

At least 5,778 people were killed, 38,568 were injured and as many as 600,000 people were displaced in the Bantul-Yogyakarta area. Most of the casualties occurred in Bantul district that lied in the epicentral region (4,143 killed and 12,026 injured).

Around 140,000 houses were destroyed and an additional 470,000 were damaged in the area, with the total loss estimated at approximately 3.14 billion US dollars. 

Felt (IX) at Bantul and Klaten, (VIII) at Sleman and Yogyakarta, (V) at Surakarta, (IV) at Salatiga and Blitar and (II) at Surabaya. Felt in much of Java. Also felt at Denpasar, Bali. 

Residents as far inland as Yogyakarta and Klaten fled inland in fear of a repeat of the 2004 tsunami, but such an event did not transpire as the earthquake was centred inland. The Solo-Yogya highway was jammed with people fleeing in panic.

Damage was not strictly a function of distance from the epicenter. Some areas of downtown Yogyakarta were seriously affected, while parts of Prambanan, which is over 10 km further from the epicenter, were severely hit. In particular, buildings alongside the Solo-Yogya road, including the ancient complex of Hindu temples, suffered substantial damage.

fields.eventnarrative:
The Yogyakarta (Southern Java) earthquake occurred about 25 km SSW of Yogyakarta and about 440 km ESE of Jakarta at 5:54 AM local time on May 27, 2006. It had moment magnitude 6.3 and its focal depth was estimated by the USGS at 17 km.

The tectonics of Java are dominated by the subduction of the Australia plate north-northeastward beneath the Sunda plate with a relative velocity of about 6 cm/year. The Australia plate dips north-northeastward from the Java trench, attaining depths of 100-200 km beneath the island of Java, and depths of 600 km north of the island. The earthquake of 26 May 2006 (UTC) occurred at shallow depth in the overriding Sunda plate well above the dipping Australia plate.
 
It is not clear if there is a direct link between the May 26 earthquake and the eruption of the Merapi volcano (that was on-going at the time), situated around 40 km north of the earthquake's epicentral area. 

(Abridged from: http://earthquake.usgs.gov/earthquakes/eqinthenews/2006/usneb6/#summary)

fields.damagescale_c:
Provided in study above: Identifies the Damage level and Mechanisms of Collapse to individual facades

The damage observed was recorded using the catalogue of mechanisms originally developed for the FaMive procedure. 

The first letter of the code represents the direction the affected facade faces, i.e N, S, E, W, with the later represented the type of collapse mechanism.

A: Vertical Overturning
D: Partial Overturning
E: Vertical Strip Overturning
B1: Overturning with 1 side wing
B2: Overturning with 2 side wings
C: Corner Failure
H: In plane failure
H2: In plane pier failure
F: Vertical Arch
G: Horizontal Arch

Some codes represent more than one facade, a comma indicates the separation.

fields.sources: Reference 1: Murakami, H., Pramitasari, D., and Ohno, R. (2008). Human Casualty and Damage Distribution in relation to Seismic Intensity in the 2006 Central Java Earthquake in Indonesia. Proceedings of the 14th World Conference on Earthquake Engineering, October 12-17, Beijing, China. Web link 1: http://www.iitk.ac.in/nicee/wcee/article/14_01-1003.PDF
fields.studynarrative: The 2006 Central Java (Yogyakarta) earthquake caused extensive damage to buildings and the loss of 5,778 lives. In the epicentral area, the intensity reached 8 or gretater on MSK scale. Murakami et al. (2008) made a reconnaissance field survey in June 2006 and collected damage and casualty data as reported by Indonesian National Government. Here, the casualty distribution in the 6 worst affected districts is provided (99.7% of the total). The greatest human toll occurred in Bantul district (71.07% of the deaths, 79.10% of the seriously injured). It should be mentioned that an additional 370 people were injured and 18 killed in 5 more districts (Boyolali, Magelang, Purworejo, Sukoharjo, Wonogiri) without other information about the injury severity distribution.
fields.authors: Murakami, Hitomi; Pramitasari, Diananta; Ohno, Ryuzo
fields.name: Murakami et al. 2008 district level casualty survey
fields.reliability_c: Data Quality Notes: "Superior" rating has been assigned to this study as the casualty figures come from official source. In addition the casualties' levels describe adequately the effect of earthquake on human life. Documentation Quality Notes: Although it is a reconnaissance report with much precious information on damage distribution, the casualties statistics are basic. Location Accuracy Notes: The geographical position of the districts has been derived from the place-name of the areas using Google Earth.

fields.sources: Reference 1: Tertulliani, A., Arcoraci, L., Berardi, M., Bernardini, F., Camassi, R., Castellano, C., Del Mese, S., Ercolani, E., Graziani, L., Leschiutta, I., Rossi, A. and Vecchi, M. (2011). An application of EMS98 in a medium-sized city: The case of L'Aquila (Central Italy) after the April 6, 2009 Mw 6.3 earthquake. Bulletin of Earthquake Engineering 9:1, 67-80. Web link 1: http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s10518-010-9188-4
fields.studynarrative: After the 2009 L'Aquila earthquake in Central Italy, a damage survey of all the buildings (1,711 buildings) in L'Aquila downtown (an area of just over 1 square kilometre) was conducted in order to evaluate the macroseismic intensity based on the European Macroseismic Scale (EMS-98).  The buildings were classified according to their type and grouped in EMS-98 vulnerability classes (A to D). The damage distribution is given for five building classes: traditional dwellings with 2 to 4 storeys (72 buildings); traditional buildings and historical edifices with 2 to 4 storeys (1,127 buildings); modern residential buildings with 2 to 6 stories and without or low anti-seismic design (458 buildings); monumental buildings such as churches, towers, etc. (31 buildings) and public and/or residential buildings with moderate anti-seismic design (8 buildings). Fifteen buildings were not surveyed (0.9% of the total). The extent of damage to each building was assessed according to the six damage grades of EMS-98, ranking from no damage to collapse. Lastly, the damage distribution and the vulnerability classes were depicted on a geo-referenced map of L'Aquila's downtown. The application of EMS-98 scale showed that intensity 8 or 9 was felt in the downtown of L'Aquila.
fields.authors: Tertulliani, A.; Arcoraci, L.; Berardi, M.; Bernardini, F.; Camassi, R.; Castellano, C.; Del Mese, S.; Ercolani, E.; Graziani, L.; Leschiutta, I.; Rossi, A.; Vecchi, M.
fields.name: Tertulliani et al 2011 L'Aquila damage survey study
fields.reliability_c: Data Quality Notes: The building classes are sufficiently defined based on EMS-98 guidelines and the number of buildings in 4 out of 5 examined building classes is adequate for statistical analysis. In addition, the sample represents the whole building stock of the downtown of L'Aquila so reliable conclusions can be drawn for each building class. Documentation Quality Notes: Superior rating has been given as the building classes and the damage grades were defined based on the guidelines of EMS-98. The context of the study is thoroughly explained. Location Accuracy Notes: The boundaries of the survey area are clearly depicted in a high resolution map derived from Google Earth.

fields.sources: Reference 1: Joint UNEP/OCHA Environment Unit (2007). Dam Integrity Assessment following the Yogyakarta Earthquake, Indonesia. Consolidated report on activities undertaken through the Monitoring and Information Center of the European Commission & the Joint UNEP/OCHA Environment Unit. Switzerland. Web link 1: http://www.gdrc.org/uem/disasters/disenvi/dam-assessment-ID.pdf
fields.studynarrative: On 27th of May 2006 a severe earthquake shook the city of Yogyakarta, Java, Indonesia and the surrounding area. In the aftermath of this humanitarian emergency, the Directorate General of Water Resources of the Ministry of Public Works officially requested assistance to assess four embankment dams possibly affected – the Sermo, the Parangjoho, the Wonogiri and the Song Putri dams. The Monitoring and Information Centre, Civil Protection Unit of the European Commission and the Joint UNEP/OCHA Environment Unit jointly offered assistance. The four dams performed satisfactorily during the earthquake. In general,  none of them failed, nor suffered significant damage, that would compromise the dam's integrity. The report descibed the minor damage to each dam in detail and provided relevant photos and other information.
fields.name: MIC and UNEP-OCHA 2007 Dam Integrity Assessment
fields.reliability_c: Data Quality Notes: Superior rating has been given since the report provided useful technical data for three out of four dams and described sufficiently the damage to each one. The photographic evidences also gave a satisfactory picture of their post-event state. Documentation Quality Notes: Superior rating has been given as the survey was conducted by experts of the field of Hydraulic Engineering and Geoscience and the purpose of the study is clear.

fields.sources: Reference 1: Raharjo W. (2007). Post-Disaster Housing in Yogyakarta, Indonesia. Resource Mobilization for Shelter Rehabilitation and Reconstruction. Paper on report 'Shelter for the Urban Poor. Proposals for Improvements – Inspired by World Urban Forum III'. Housing Development & Management. Lund University, Sweden. Reference 2: EERI Special Earthquake Report (2006). The Mw 6.3 Java, Indonesia, Earthquake of May 27, 2006. Web link 1: http://lup.lub.lu.se/luur/download?func=downloadFile&recordOId=1503795&fileOId=1503800 Web link 2: https://www.eeri.org/lfe/pdf/indonesia_java_eeri_prelim_report.pdf
fields.studynarrative: On 27 May 2006 an 6.3 Mw earthquake hit the provinces of Yogyakarta and Central Java. The worst affected regencies were Bantul in Yogyakarta province and Klaten in Central Java province. In Bantul regency the Jetis, Pundong, Plered and Bambang Lipuro districts were the most severely damaged. In these 4 districts the ratio of totally destroyed dwellings exceeded 63%. The damage distribution of the dwellings in the 17 districts of Bantul Regency presented here originate from the Indonesian National Government (BAKORNAS-Civil Protection Agency) and appeared in a press release of July 1, 2006 (Kompas National Daily Newspaper), i.e. 7 weeks after the earthquake by which time damage surveys in the area were nearly completed. Therefore the data concern nearly the total of housing units existing in each district (216,842 housing units in the whole regency). Raharjo (2007) made no reference for the residential buildings' characteristics or any distinction between structural classes. As a result the damage distributions are for nearly the whole housing stock in each district regardless of dwelling type. Three damage levels were defined (light damage, heavy damage, totally destroyed). The composition of the housing stock in Bantul regency (a rural area to the South of Yogyakarta city), consisted mostly of non-engineered load-bearing masonry structures (those built pre-1990 being mostly unreinforced brick masonry or confined or partially confined brick masonry; while those built post-1990 were mostly reinforced concrete confined or partially confined brick masonry). Study Notes: From inspection of the data relative to the 2010 census' population in these 17 districts (from Statistics Indonesia) we believe that the damage survey in Bantul Regency covered nearly the entire dwelling stock in all the districts. The light damage category may also contain dwellings that were undamaged, particularly in those districts where shaking and damage was less severe (e.g. Sanden, Sedayu, Kasihan, Srandakan etc.), while in the the most severely affected districts (Jetis, Pundong, Plered, Babang Lipuro) no dwellings were undamaged.
fields.name: Raharjo 2007 District Level Study (Bantul Regency)
fields.reliability_c: Data Quality Notes: Average rating has been given since the data set is for all the dwelings regardless of structural class and the damage levels lack any description. However, the sample in each district is statistically adequate and represents nearly the complete dwelling stock of each district. Documentation Quality Notes: The primary reference is not actually suitable for vunerability studies, it is a report on the challenges faced by actors involved in the rehabilitation and reconstruction of settlements. For this reason, it has no information about the survey process and teams. On the other hand the data set provided is an overall presentation of the damage in Bantul Regency's 17 districts and useful when taking into account the broad characteristics of the dwelling stock in the study area. Location Accuracy Notes: The boundaries of each district have been derived from Yogyakarta district level map (as defined by Badan Pusat Statistik) using GADM administrative level 2 shapefile.

fields.sources: Reference 1: D’Ayala, D. F. and Paganoni, S. (2009) Assessment and analysis of damage in L’Aquila historic city centre after 6th April 2009. Bulletin of Earthquake Engineering 9:1, 81-104. Web link 1: http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/s10518-010-9224-4
fields.studynarrative: This study describes the output of a building by building (and facade by facade) survey carried out in the district of L’Aquila, Italy, in May 2009 after the April earthquake and later in January 2010. Observations collected on site regard stone and brick masonry buildings of the historic centre of L’Aquila; particular focus was given to a number of buildings of interest, which better represent two locally recurrent building typologies: the mansion and the common dwelling. A description of the main structural features and their influence on damage mechanism is provided, stressing the importance of elements such as wall lay-out, quality of masonry and strengthening interventions. (Adapted from paper abstract) Study Notes: This is a very comprehensive study with clearly labeled and annotated maps
fields.name: D’Ayala and Paganoni 2011 Historic City Centre Study
fields.reliability_c: Data Quality Notes: The study is very detailed as to form of construction, details of damage, cause of damage, and there is photograophic evidence for the post-event damage, from field photos. All the daya was collected in an on-site survey Documentation Quality Notes: The study identifies clearly the classes of buildings; it clearly explains the context of the study (a detailed academic study), and the composition of the damage assessment team.

fields.name: Asset no. 4: Sermo Dam
fields.location_c: Georeference source: Study Reference 1 Damage description: The embankment was permanently displaced. Especially between elevations 100 to 125 m, i.e. 20 to 45 m below the dam crest, a compaction and deflection of the dam body was caused. The deformations accumulate to vertical settlement and horizontal displacements of about 50mm. The original riprap had to be rehabilitated. Source of damage data: Study Reference 1, pg. 7 Asset location accuracy rating: Superior Asset location accuracy justification: Geo-coordinate on the dam's crest is given in the report (in degrees, decimal minutes) and have been checked through Google Earth.

fields.inventoryclass_c: The earthquake caused the collapse of 17 five-story Reinforced Concrete apartment buildings (of the 1-447C series), with 80 apartments each (1360 dwelling units), as well as 4 apartment buildings with 16 apartments each (64 dwelling units), the town hall, the administration building, a heat generating building, one of the two wings of the school building and a number of shops. The deaths occurred in the 22 residential buildings due to the time of occurrence (00:03 am local time).

fields.inventoryclass_c: Type A are usually traditional stone masonry buildings of two or three stories which have been the dominant building type in the area for many centuries; mostly consist of a coarse, short-bedded, ill-laid rubble masonry with great thickness of mortar joints and very thcik walls. Many have had additional stories added in new materials without strengthening the supporting structure. Fir timber made up the floor joists and roof rafters, but are often replaced by concrete floors supported by steel joists and ceramic planks that are not bonded together laterally nor tied into the walls.
fields.description: Random rubble masonry, timber or steel joist floors; tile on timber roofs
fields.name: A

fields.inventoryclass_c: Type B mostly consist of better-built older stone masonry buildings with dressed stone outer skins and well bonded corners; many are of manufactured masonry units, concrete block, brick or hollow ceramic block, and have reinforced concrete floors and eaves slabs continuous through the walls and also connected together laterally.
fields.description: consist of two types of buildings; combined because performance was not significantly different: dressed stone, brick or block masonry with or without reinforced concrete floors or ring beams
fields.name: B

fields.inventoryclass_c: Majority of recent buildings are of Type C, reinforced concrete frame buildings; their floors and roofs commonly consist of in-situ reinforced filler slabs with ceramic plank fillers, supported on an often irregular grid of square columns; both internal and extranal infill walls often consist of double-skin hollow, loosely-bonded ceramic block; external walls are sometimes of concrete block.
fields.name: C

fields.inventoryclass_c: Masonry with RC frame in the first one or two stories with ERD (Earthquake Resistant Design); 500 buildings situated in areas of intensity VII to XI. 176 were designed for I=VI; 316 for I=VII and 8 for I=VIII (most according to Code for Seismic Design of Buildings, GB 50011-2001, January 2001; some according to Code for Seismic Design of Buildings, GBJ 11-89, January 1991). The ground storey in these buildings consists of reinforced concrete frame with masonry infill, while the upper floors (up to 5 more levels) consist of unreinforced load-bearing brick masonry. We assign this class to RC frame system with vertical irregularity (change in vertical structure).
fields.name: Bottom Frame buildings with ERD

fields.inventoryclass_c: High-rise (8 to 20 or more storeys) RC frame or dual RC frame-shear wall with 2001 code ERD (earthquake resistant design); 60 buildings situated in areas of intensity VII to VIII. 43 were designed for I=VI; 11 for I=VII and 6 for I=VIII (Code for Seismic Design of Buildings, GB 50011-2001, January 2001). fields.inventoryclass_c: This category includes 226,750 reinforced concrete (RC) frame buildings with infill masonry walls and mixed structure buildings (reinforced concrete frame with infill walls, vertical or horizontal or vertical and horizontal extensions to pre-existing unreinforced masonry buildings) in the MM intensity zones 7 to 9. The number of buildings in MM intensity zones 5 and 6 is not reported. These buildings were constructed prior to the upgrade of the 1959 Greek earthquake code (based on allowable stress design) in 1985 and include pre-code buildings (built before 1959). The incidence of mixed structure in this class is 33.3% of the inspected buildings in the municipalities with MM intensity 7, 8 and 9.
fields.name: RC1-MIX1, before 1985

fields.inventoryclass_c: This category includes 36,502 reinforced concrete (RC) ductile frame or dual frame-shear wall buildings with infill masonry walls and mixed structure buildings (reinforced concrete frame with infill walls, vertical or horizontal or vertical and horizontal extensions to pre-existing unreinforced masonry buildings) in the MM intensity zones 7 to 9. The number of buildings in MM intensity zones 5 and 6 is not reported. These buildings were constructed in the period 1985-1995 (using the allowable stress design code of 1985, which introduced the concept of ductile frames and wide columns). In this period RC buildings constructed on pilotis (soft-storey at ground floor level) were designed taking this fact into account, with columns being more substantial and more dense. The incidence of mixed structure buildings in this class is 10.7% of the inspected buildings in the municipalities with MM intensity 7, 8 and 9.
fields.name: RC2-MIX2, 1985-1995

fields.inventoryclass_c: This category includes 19,384 reinforced concrete (RC) frame or dual frame-shear wall buildings with infill masonry walls and mixed structure buildings (reinforced concrete frame with infill walls, vertical or horizontal or vertical and horizontal extensions to pre-existing unreinforced masonry buildings) in the MM intensity zones 7 to 9. The number of buildings in MM intensity zones 5 and 6 is not reported. These buildings were constructed in the period 1996-1999 (with the modern 1995 Greek Earthquake Design Code, which is based on ultimate strength design employing dynamic structural analysis with use of response spectra). The incidence of mixed structure buildings in this class is only 5% of the inspected buildings in the municipalities with MM intensity 7, 8 and 9.
fields.name: RC3-MIX3, after 1995

fields.inventoryclass_c: This category includes 39,055 unreinforced masonry buildings with load-bearing wall of any of the following types: solid clay brick, horizontally perforated clay brick, hollow concrete block or any mixture of these, in the MM intensity zones 7 to 9. The number of buildings in MM intensity zones 5 and 6 is not reported. The horizontal structure is usually reinforced concrete slabs and less frequently wooden or metal floors.
fields.name: MAS

fields.inventoryclass_c: This category includes 29,244 other buildings of the following building classes: unreinforced load-bearing masonry with walls made of adobe blocks, rubble stone, hewn stone or any mixture of these plus metal frame and wood frame buildings, in the MM intensity zones 7 to 9. The number of buildings in MM intensity zones 5 and 6 is not reported. The ratio of metal and wood frame buildings is 8.8, 34.5 and 58.7%, respectively in the intensity 7, 8 and 9 zones. The proportion of wood frame buildings in the intensity zones 7 to 9 is only 3.1%.
fields.name: OTH

fields.inventoryclass_c: Around 83.5% of the houses in the affected region were predominantly single story unreinforced rubble stone masonry laid on mud mortar with roof from heavy, flat compacted earth (circa 60% of the cases) or corrugated iron sheets (circa 30% of the cases), supported by wooden beams resting on the thick (0.6 -1 m) walls or on sub-loadbearing (hybrid) systems of timber columns that support the beams and roofs. An additional 9% of the houses were unreinforced rubble stone masonry laid on cement mortar. Just over 1.5% of the houses were brick masonry laid on cement mortar (often with a reinforced concrete slab as roof), and the remaining 1% were dry stone masonry and 5% wooden houses with thatched or corrupgated iron sheet roof. Reinforced concrete slabs for floors and (or) roofs were found in just 3% of the buildings. On the peripheries of each village  thatched houses are found (housing the poorest people) which consist of wooden posts with a raftered thatch roof and thatch panel walls. Very few engineered structures (mostly without earthquake resistant design) were found in the largest villages/towns (e.g. Killari, Jevli etc.) and include mostly public buildings such as hospitals,clinics, government offices, post offices, banks etc. consisting of reinforced concrete frame with infill brick masonry wall structure.
fields.name: All buildings

fields.inventoryclass_c: Include both older and newer steel buildings:Older ones are "a typical Japanese type of steel building construction was developed in the early 1960's in answer to steel shortages and the high cost of structural steel in Japan. Many of these buildings, designed and constructed without much regard for seismic considerations, suffered a considerable amount of a damage during this earthquake. The potential ductility of these buildings is severely limited as the cold-formed steel sections used for columns will typically develop local buckling prior to attainments of their plastic movement capacity." Newer ones are "as steel structures are frequently hidden behind fireproofing coatings are architectural finishes, it will take more time before the full extent of damage to steel b buildings is known. However, at the time of writing, some new steel buildings were known to have suffered important damage."
fields.name: Steel

fields.inventoryclass_c: There are three type of brick masonry buildings in Sichuan Province: a) with normal earthquake-resistant design built after 1992 (in most cases/locations design intensity level = VII on the Chinese Intensity Scale); b) without earthquake-resistant design or with some incomplete seismic measures built prior to 1993 (incl. factories and public buildings built in the 1980's); and c) informal-sector self-built residential or mixed residential-commercial buildings, neither specially  designed, nor considering earthquake resistance protection, but mostly using RC ring beams and partial RC column-beam at ground floor level (but only in the front part), generally with two storeys, but some are up to 4 or 5 storeys. The building class label given here is derived by reading relevant sections in the report.
fields.name: Brick Masonry (with or without ERD, incl. informal-sector housing); 2 to 6 floors; 1970-2007

The exterior and interior walls of some were made of rubble, undressed or coarsely dressed stones but in other buildings the exterior walls were made of stones while the interior walls were made of bricks. Earthquake resistance was not generally considered in the design of these buildings.  No information on the horizontal structure of these buildings is given.

No information on the horizontal structure of these buildings is given.
fields.name: Multistory brick-stone wall structures

fields.inventoryclass_c: Reinforced Concrete Frame, prior to 1960. Cast in-situ reinforced concrete beam and column arrangements, with hollow clay brick infill, constructed without any seismic code. Typically, they have reinforced concrete flat slabs or low-pitch (15°-20°) roofs constructed with timber frames and covered in tiles. They have up to 4 storeys. Very few RC buildings in Lefkada Island have the common in Greece soft-storey, as the island is on Greece's highest seismicity zone.
fields.name: Reinforced Concrete, pre-code, 1-4 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Reinforced Concrete Frame, 1960 seismic code. Cast in-situ reinforced concrete beam and column arrangements, with hollow clay brick infill, constructed between 1960 and 1984  under the guidelines of the first seismic code of Greece. Typically, they have reinforced concrete flat slabs or low-pitch (15°-20°) roofs constructed with timber frames and covered in tiles. They have up to 4 storeys. Very few RC buildings in Lefkada Island have the common in Greece soft-storey, as the island is on Greece's highest seismicity zone.
fields.name: Reinforced Concrete, 1960 ERD code, 1-4 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Reinforced Concrete Frame, 1984 seismic code. Cast in-situ reinforced concrete beam and column arrangements, with hollow clay brick infill, constructed between 1985 and 1994. They may include shear walls in the form of wide-columns, since they became gradually more common in Greece after the revision of the early (1959) seismic code in 1984. Typically, they have reinforced concrete flat slabs or low-pitch (15°-20°) roofs constructed with timber frames and covered in tiles. They have up to 4 storeys. Very few RC buildings in Lefkada Island have the common in Greece soft-storey, as the island is on Greece's highest seismicity zone.
fields.name: Reinforced Concrete, 1984 ERD code, 1-4 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Reinforced Concrete Frame, 1984 seismic code. Cast in-situ reinforced concrete beam and column arrangements, with hollow clay brick infill, constructed between 1985 and 1994. They may include shear walls in the form of wide-columns, since they became gradually more common in Greece after the revision of the early (1959) seismic code in 1984. Typically, they have reinforced concrete flat slabs or low-pitch (15°-20°) roofs constructed with timber frames and covered in tiles. They have up to 4 storeys. Very few RC buildings in Lefkada Island have the common in Greece soft-storey, as the island is on Greece's highest seismicity zone.
fields.name: Reinforced Concrete, 1995 ERD code, 1-4 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Reinforced Concrete Frame, 2000 seismic code. Cast in-situ reinforced concrete beam and column arrangements, with hollow clay brick infill, constructed post 2000. They include shear walls in the form of wide-columns, since they became common practice in Greece after the revision of the interim (1984) seismic code in 1995. Typically, they have reinforced concrete flat slabs or low-pitch (15°-20°) roofs constructed with timber frames and covered in tiles.  They have up to 4 storeys. Very few RC buildings in Lefkada Island have the common in Greece soft-storey, as the island is on Greece's highest seismicity zone.
fields.name: Reinforced Concrete, 2000 ERD code, 1-4 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Load Bearing Cut or Rubble Stone Masonry built prior to 1919. Stone masonry walls of thickness varying from 60cm to 1m and height of up to 3m per storey. Lime or pozzolanic mortar is commonly used in the construction of walls, consisting generally of two loosely interlocked wythes, the external being in cut or rubble stone and the internal in rubble stone. The floors are made of timber beams covered with wooden planks and usually supported on timber sole beams resting on the stone masonry around its perimeter. Most structures have wooden pitched roofs with 25°-30° slopes covered with clay tiles; gable walls are also common.
fields.name: Unreinforced Cut or Rubble Stone Masonry, prior to 1919, 1-2 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Load Bearing Cut or Rubble Stone Masonry built during the period 1919-1945. Stone masonry walls of thickness varying from 60cm to 1m and height of up to 3m per storey. Lime or pozzolanic mortar is commonly used in the construction of walls, consisting generally of two loosely interlocked wythes, the external being in cut or rubble stone and the internal in rubble stone. The mortar used was pozzolanic or lime. The floors are made of timber beams covered with wooden planks and usually supported on timber sole beams resting on the stone masonry around its perimeter. Most structures have wooden pitched roofs with 25°-30° slopes covered with clay tiles; gable walls are also common.
fields.name: Unreinforced Cut or Rubble Stone Masonry, 1919-1945, 1-2 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Load Bearing Cut or Rubble Stone Masonry built during the period 1946-1960. Stone masonry walls of thickness varying from 60cm to 1m and height of up to 3m per storey. Lime or pozzolanic mortar is commonly used in the construction of walls, consisting generally of two loosely interlocked wythes, the external being in cut or rubble stone and the internal in rubble stone. The floors are made of timber beams covered with wooden planks and usually supported on timber sole beams resting on the stone masonry around its perimeter. Most structures have wooden pitched roofs with 25°-30° slopes covered with clay tiles; gable walls are also common.
fields.name: Unreinforced Cut or Rubble Stone Masonry, 1946-1960, 1-2 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Load Bearing Stone Masonry Structures, post 1960. Stone masonry walls of thickness varying from 60cm to 1m and height of up to 3m. Cement mortar is commonly used in the construction of walls, consisting generally of two loosely interlocked wythes, the external being in cut or rubble stone and the internal in rubble stone. The floors are made of timber beams covered with wooden planks and usually supported on timber sole beams resting on the stone masonry around its perimeter or from reinforced concrete slabs. Most structures have wooden pitched roofs with 25°-30° slopes covered with clay tiles; gable walls are also common.
fields.name: Unreinforced Cut or Rubble Stone Masonry, post 1960, 1-2 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Stone or Brick Masonry confined in Reinforced Concrete, built prior to 1960. Mixed system comprising of load-bearing stone or brick masonry walls confined in reinforced concrete (RC) vertical and horizontal elements, not designed to behave as moment-resisting frames. RC ring beams are often used at mid-height and on top of the masonry walls, enhancing the bonding of the units, tying the walls together, and improving their out-of-plane stiffness. They have cast in-situ RC slabs, although, in cases, timber joist and sheathing boards are also used. Their roofs are timber trusses.
fields.name: Stone or Brick Masonry confined in Reinforced Concrete, prior to 1960, 1-2 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Stone or Brick Masonry confined in Reinforced Concrete, built in the period 1960 to 1985. Mixed system comprising of load-bearing stone or brick masonry walls confined in reinforced concrete (RC) vertical and horizontal elements, not designed to behave as moment-resisting frames. RC ring beams are often used at mid-height and on top of the masonry walls, enhancing the bonding of the units, tying the walls together, and improving their out-of-plane stiffness. They have cast in-situ RC slabs, although, in cases, timber joist and sheathing boards are also used. Their roofs are timber trusses.
fields.name: Stone or Brick Masonry confined in Reinforced Concrete, 1960-1985, 1-2 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Stone or Brick Masonry confined in Reinforced Concrete, built post 1985. Mixed system comprising of load-bearing stone or brick masonry walls confined in reinforced concrete (RC) vertical and horizontal elements, not designed to behave as moment-resisting frames. RC ring beams are often used at mid-height and on top of the masonry walls, enhancing the bonding of the units, tying the walls together, and improving their out-of-plane stiffness. They have cast in-situ RC slabs, although, in cases, timber joist and sheathing boards are also used. Their roofs are timber trusses.
fields.description: Load bearing stone/brick masonry and reinforced concrete load bearing element buildings constructed post 1985 (including 1985)
fields.name: Stone or Brick Masonry confined in Reinforced Concrete, post 1985, 1-2 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Timber Frame structures built in the 1900-2000 period cover 4% of the islands building stock. Timber frames (post and beam type) with locally supplied timber from the island's oak, cypress, pine, fir, and olive tree reserves. Olive tree branches were favoured for the construction of corner elbows given their natural flexibility, while oak was used primarily for the construction of the basic frame and the lateral stiffening members. Floors made of timber joists covered on top with wooden planks. The roofs are timber trusses similar to those of the stone masonry class.
fields.name: Timber Frame

fields.inventoryclass_c: Dual load-bearing stone masonry and timber frame structures, built prior to 1945. A vernacular structural system unique to the Lefkada Island, locally known as pontelarisma. Typically it consists of two storeys with stone masonry on the ground storey and timber frame on the upper level. The upper level is supported by the masonry of the ground storey, as well as an additional set of timber columns erected in the interior of the ground storey. Floors are made of timber joists covered with wooden planks. The roofs are timber trusses.
fields.name: Stone Masonry with internal Timber Columns, prior to 1945, 1-2 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Dual load-bearing stone masonry and timber frame structures, built post 1945. A vernacular structural system unique to the Lefkada Island, locally known as pontelarisma. Typically it consists of two storeys with stone masonry on the ground storey and timber frame on the upper level. The upper level is supported by the masonry of the ground storey, as well as an additional set of timber columns erected in the interior of the ground storey. Floors are made of timber joists covered with wooden planks. The roofs are timber trusses.
fields.name: Stone Masonry with internal Timber Columns, post 1945, 1-2 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: 4 to 6 storeys RC apartment buildings, constructed in the period 1963-1989 according to the 1963 or 1978/1981 Romanian earthquake codes' requirements for seismic zone of MSK intensity VIII. Locations: Buzau and Valenii de Munte (40 and 17 buildings respectively).
fields.name: Dual RC Frame-Shear Wall and (or) Large Precast RC Panel, 4-6 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: 4 or 5 storeyed dual RC frame-shear wall buildings of various occupancies (incl. public, commercial and apartment blocks), constructed in the period 1963-1989 according to the 1963 and 1978/1981 Romanian earthquake codes' requirements for seismic zone of MSK intensity IX. Location: Focsani (19 buildings, of which 93% were 4 or 5 storeyed).
fields.name: Dual RC Frame-Shear Wall, 4-5 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: 4 or 5 storeyed Large Precast RC Panel (sheal wall) buildings (incl. public, commercial and apartment blocks), constructed in the period 1963-1989 according to the 1963 and 1978/1981 Romanian earthquake codes' requirements for seismic zone of MSK intensity IX. Location: Focsani (23 buildings, of which 93% were 4 or 5 storeyed).
fields.name: Large Precast RC Panel (sheal wall), 4-5 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: This is the most common single-family residential load-bearing masonry building type in Romania. They are commonly one or two-storeyed with a timber roof covered by various types of materials (clay tiles, sandstones, corrugated iron sheets etc.). Their architectural layout is more elaborate and less symmetrical, with verandas, porches and various ornamental elements on the facades. Older urban area buildings have a significantly larger storey height, sometimes exceeding 3.5 metres. The horizontal structure is either wooden or masonry vault, while in newer buildings RC slabs are also being used. Foundations in older buildings are made from stones laid in lime mortar, in more recent buildings, concrete foundations are also used. Some are reinforced either with RC lintels and (or) with RC ring beams.
fields.name: Brick Masonry, 1-2 storeys

fields.inventoryclass_c: Adobe and Compacted Clay buildings are commonly found in most rural parts of eastern and southern Romania, but also in many cities. They are usually old, single-family houses of one storey with a very simple rectangular layout. Their walls are thick (40-60cm), made from raw adobe blocks (mixed with straws) or compacted clay (with horizontal tree branches), and laid with low strength mortar (clay or mud mixed with sand) and plastered with lime-sand mixture. In newer buildings, the plaster is reinforced with a wire mesh that is nailed onto the walls. They usually have shallow foundation made from river cobbles. Both of these building classes are almost exclusively single storeyed with internal height below 3m and a timber roof, covered by various types of materials (thatch, clay tiles, sandstones, corrugated iron sheets etc.). In more recent buildings, concrete foundations are also used.
fields.name: Adobe and (or) Compacted Clay buildings, 1 storey

fields.inventoryclass_c: These buildings have mostly 6 to 12 storeys built mostly before 1950, without earthquake resistant design and without concern for adequate structural layout and detailing. In many cases the columns were not continuous through the entire height of a building and there was no concern for creating moment-resisting nodes. The reinforced concrete frame transmitted part of the gravity loads to the ground and served to confine the infill masonry which played essential role in resisting lateral loads. 20 buildings of this class situated mostly in street corners collapsed in Bucharest city centre during the 1977 earthquake (8 are included in this survey), almost all had been built before 1941 and had been damaged during the November 1940 Vrancea earthquake.
fields.name: RC Frame structures, mostly 6-12 storeys, mostly pre-1950

fields.inventoryclass_c: Reinforced concrete shear wall structures represented the bulk of the high-rise building stock built during the two decades prior to 1977. There was a wide range of layouts and construction techniques. Construction was based on the use of sliding forms (in the earlier stage), steel forms or dismountable timber forms. The floors were as a rule prefabricated (half-panels). Long buildings had according to different design one or two internal longitudinal shear walls. The transverse walls were spaced at intervals corresponding to the width of the room (between 3 and 4m).
fields.name: RC Shear Wall, mostly 10-11 storeys, shear walls at small intervals (3-4 m)

fields.inventoryclass_c: Several buildings were characterized by wide spacing (>4m) of the shear walls, aimed at allowing more architectural freedom in designing the apartments. These buildings were designed and erected under conditions similar to those of the previous class of buildings.
fields.name: RC Shear Wall, mostly 10-11 storeys, shear walls at large intervals (>4m)

fields.inventoryclass_c: Relatively old buildings (most built before 1900) and of low-quality materials (adobe type, wooden structures with earth fill etc.). They were in no case engineered. They were usually of one storey, with roofs of timber.
fields.name: Buildings of low quality material, 1 storey, mostly pre-1900

fields.inventoryclass_c: Mostly of one or two storeys but occasionally of four or five storeys. Their shape was in many cases irregular, and highly non-symmetric. The quality of the masory was variable, ranging from poor to excellent, though high quality masonry was found even in some poor small houses. The poorer houses often lacked proper foundations especially when there was no basement. The floors were usually of wood over masonry vaults supported by steel beams.
fields.name: Masonry bearing walls with flexible floors, 1-5 storeys, up to 1940

fields.inventoryclass_c: Similar to the previous class, but built after the war. The proportion of these buildings in the total building stock tended to decrease with time due to the increasing use of reinforced concrete in the construction of floors. This construction system was nevertheless widely used, especially for small one-storey buildings.
fields.name: Masonry bearing walls with flexible floors, 1-5 storeys, post 1940

fields.inventoryclass_c: The general features of these buildings are similar to those of the above classes, except that the floors were of reinforced concrete. The presence of reinforced concrete slabs, usually including girders, and of reinforced concrete lintels, sometimes cast together with the floors, had a strongly favourable influence on earthquake performance.
fields.name: Masonry bearing walls with rigid floors, 2-5 storeys, up to 1940

fields.inventoryclass_c: These buildings represented, up to 1970, the bulk of the low-rise building stock. Most of these buildings were designed to resist seismic action. Various construction systems were used. The policy of industrialising construction activities led to the use of prefabricated floors (usually strips but, in the earlier days, beams with infill pieces). Constant attention was paid, especially after 1960, to the use of reinforced concrete members to improve the performance of bearing masonry. Besides the use of girders, vertical members at corners and wall crossing became common. The use of reinforced concrete members (horizontal and vertical) with a confining role contributed much to the increase of strength and conferred on masonry buildings a significant degree of ductility. There were nevertheless cases where the use of prefabricated floors was not accompanied by measures to transform the floors into truly rigid diaphragms.
fields.name: Masonry bearing walls with rigid floors, 2-5 storeys, post 1940

fields.inventoryclass_c: Old non-engineered, 1-4  storey residential, industrial or socio-cultural buildings of usually irregular plan, with flooring of steel beams with masonry elements or masonry vaults or wood, built on stone foundations and situated in the old parts of Jassy city. They have thick walls and may or may not have basements. The age of some of these buildings exceeded 100 years in 1977. Most were 1-2 storeyed brick masonry structures.
fields.name: Old Masonry, 1-4 storeys, pre-1940

fields.inventoryclass_c: These buildings were erected between 1950 and 1970. They were up to 5 storeys high. Longitudinal and transverse walls had comparable stiffnesses. Reinforced concrete girders were used at all levels, including the foundation. Load-bearing wall material not specified.
fields.name: Masonry with cast-in-place RC floors, 2-5 storeys, 1950-1970

fields.inventoryclass_c: These 5-storey buildings constructed around the 1960-1976 period have transverse walls and single median longitudinal walls interrupted by the staircase. The floors are of precast strips supported by the transverse walls. The foundations are of concrete with reinforced concrete girders. Load-bearing wall material not specified.
fields.name: Masonry with precast RC floors, 5 storeys, 1960-1976

fields.inventoryclass_c: The buildings in this class were all five storeyed and built according to designs developed at the institutes in Bucharest and Jassy. The only differences were in the types of panels and/or joints. All structures had transverse walls confining the rooms and the staircases and pairs of longitudinal median walls without openings, confining the staircases. They were built either on contractile clay with high water table (intensity VII+) or on loess (intensity VI+).
fields.name: Large RC panels, 5 storeys, mostly 1963-1976

fields.inventoryclass_c: Several types of structures belong inthis class: common cast-in-place RC framed structures with cast-in-place floors or of precast slabs; RC frame structures with cast-in-place columns, cast-in-place or precast beams and floors of precast slabs; composite RC framed structures with shear walls. The infill and separation walls are of brick masonry or light-weight concrete blocks. In all cases there was a rigid basement and a foundation mat. Their layout was almost perfectly symmetrical. They were either 8 or 11 storeyed.
fields.name: RC frame or dual frame-shear wall, 8-11 storeys, mostly 1955-1976

fields.inventoryclass_c: Reinforced concrete shear wall buildings with 8 to 11 storeys using three different types of forms. Floors were cast-in-place except when steel forms were used, in which case they were precast. Foundations were designed as general mats, leading to a rigid basement box. A single internal longitudinal shear wall was used. Weaknesses observed in: general plan layout, stiffness distribution and connections between members.
fields.name: RC shear wall, 8-11 storeys, mostly 1966-1976

fields.inventoryclass_c: This category includes (a) stone or pebble masonry buildings of poor quality or irregular layout; (b) hewn stone or brick masonry buildings of good quality with regular layout. Their horizontal structure is either vault (with or without ties) or flexible (wooden). Most of these buildings had no wall ties or tie beams. Some of the stone/pebble buildings had semirigid floors and some had wall ties or tie beams. For more details see Figure 9 in the paper.
fields.retrofit: some had wall ties or tie beams
fields.name: Masonry-A

fields.inventoryclass_c: This category includes (a) stone or pebble masonry buildings of poor quality or irregular layout; (b) hewn stone or brick masonry buildings of good quality with regular layout. The horizontal structure of (a) is either vault (with ties) or flexible (wooden) or semirigid or rigid, while in the case of (b) is vault (with or without ties) or flexible (wooden). Most of these buildings had wall ties or tie beams. For more details see Figure 9 in the paper.
fields.retrofit: Most of these buildings had wall ties or tie beams
fields.name: Masonry-B

fields.inventoryclass_c: This category includes hewn stone or brick masonry buildings of good quality with regular layout. The horizontal structure is either semirigid or rigid. They have wall ties or tie beams but buildings with rigid floor had no wall ties or tie beams. For more details see Figure 9 in the paper.
fields.retrofit: They have wall ties or tie beams but buildings with rigid floor had no wall ties or tie beams
fields.name: Masonry-C

fields.inventoryclass_c: The housing units of Bantul Regency (a rural area to the south of Yogyakarta City) can be divided into three general categories: 1) unreinforced masonry-older houses (pre-1990) consisting of unreinforced fired clay brick masonry walls with flexible, pitched or hipped timber truss or bamboo roofs with clay tiles; 2) confined or partially confined masonry-newer houses (post-1990) built of reinforced concrete confined or partially confined brick, solid concrete block or stone masonry in cement mortar walls with flexible, pitched or hipped timber truss or bamboo roofs covered by clay tiles; and 3) timber frame-less common and often with some masonry walls.

fields.inventoryclass_c:
Distribution of number of stories within each district is available in the report.

Buildings were not aggregated in terms of lateral load resisting system. However, majority of 4 to 6 storeys buildings were moment frames at that time. Therefore, lateral load resisting system is defined as moment frames, altough inventory class name includes terms for both moment resisting frames and dual frame wall systems.
fields.name: 4 to 6 storey RC Buildings with moment frames or with shear walls and moment frames together for lateral load resistance (contains only the damaged buildings)

fields.inventoryclass_c: Construction description: The Valentin Valiente School consisted of two similar, independent two-story buildings. They were typical school buildings built about 50 years ago and defined as Old-type schools. The height of each story was 3m. Each building had reinforced concrete frames. Most columns had a 20-cm x 30-cm cross section, with the smaller dimension along the longitudinal direction of the building. Frames with beams (20-cm wide by 65-cm deep) were located along the transverse direction of the building, with no beams along the longitudinal direction. The concrete joist floor system was 25-cm thick and had a 5-cm slab with ribs along the longitudinal direction spaced 50-cm apart. A mean concrete strength of 14Mpa was obtained from testing. Yield stresses were 235 and 276 MPa for the longitudinal and transverse reinforcement bars, respectively. Transverse reinforcement consisted of plain bars of 1/4-inc diameter set 25-cm on center in beams and 15-cm in columns; no transverse reinforcement was placed at the joints. Masonry infill, made of 15-cm thick hollow concrete blocks, completely filled the transverse frames. Short columns with 55 cm clear length were generated by the 1,70-m masonry infill that partially filled the longitudinal frame.
fields.name: 199707091924, Reducing Seismic Risk of School Buildings in Venezuela., 1

fields.inventoryclass_c: Construction description: The Raimundo Martinez Centeno school buildings were designed in 1978 and built in 1985. They were typical school buildings defined as Box type schools. Although the structures had been designed for Zone 2 of the 1967 Seismic Code, they were built in Cariaco (Zone 3). The school consisted of two similar, independent buildings, each with a C-shaped floor plan. The three-story Building had reinforced concrete frames along both horizontal directions and masonry infill of 15 cm thick hollow clay blocks. The concrete joist floor system was 30-cm deep with ribs along the north-south direction. Column cross-sections were 35 cm x 35 cm and beam cross sections were 30 cm x 40 cm and 30 cm x 70 cm wide and deep, respectively. The heigh of each story was 3,10 m. Short columns of 70 cm in length were created by the masonry infill in some columns. Column hoops of 3/8-inch diameter were installed 10 cm on center near the joints and 20 cm further away from the joints, with no transverse reinforcement at the joints. Mean values obtained from tests for the concrete strength, 25 MPa, and steel yield stress, 414 MPa, complied with the values specified in construction plans.
fields.name: 199707091924, Reducing Seismic Risk of School Buildings in Venezuela., 2
